WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.760
Happy Thursday, everybody, and welcome to the Data Science Hangout.

00:00:15.760 --> 00:00:18.559
Hope everybody is having a great week.

00:00:18.559 --> 00:00:23.240
If we haven't had a chance to meet yet, I'm Rachel, it's so nice to meet you.

00:00:23.240 --> 00:00:28.080
If it is your first time joining us at the Hangout, let us know in the chat so we can

00:00:28.080 --> 00:00:30.660
all welcome you in as well.

00:00:30.660 --> 00:00:35.680
This is our open space to chat about data science leadership, questions you're facing,

00:00:35.680 --> 00:00:40.680
and getting to hear about what's going on in the world of data across different industries.

00:00:40.680 --> 00:00:45.080
So every week, we get to feature a different data science leader as my co-host here to

00:00:45.080 --> 00:00:48.840
help lead our discussion and answer questions from you all.

00:00:48.840 --> 00:00:53.639
So together, we're all dedicated to making this a welcoming environment for everybody.

00:00:53.959 --> 00:00:59.160
I love to hear from everyone, no matter your level of experience or area of work or background.

00:01:00.119 --> 00:01:03.560
It's also totally okay to just listen in if you want.

00:01:03.560 --> 00:01:08.519
There's also three ways to ask questions and provide your own perspective on certain topics

00:01:08.519 --> 00:01:09.019
too.

00:01:09.720 --> 00:01:13.400
So you can jump in by raising your hand on Zoom.

00:01:14.279 --> 00:01:19.320
You can put questions into the Zoom chat and feel free to just put a little star next to

00:01:19.320 --> 00:01:23.160
it if you're in a coffee shop or something or your dog's barking and you want me to read

00:01:23.160 --> 00:01:23.720
it instead.

00:01:24.440 --> 00:01:30.919
We also have a Slido link which my colleagues will share here in the chat in just a second

00:01:30.919 --> 00:01:33.559
where you can also ask questions anonymously.

00:01:34.440 --> 00:01:40.199
We do share the recordings of each session up to the Posit YouTube and the Hangout site

00:01:40.199 --> 00:01:43.959
so you can always go back and re-watch or share with a friend.

00:01:44.919 --> 00:01:48.919
But with all that, thank you all for joining us again this Thursday and thank you so much

00:01:48.919 --> 00:01:50.760
Art for joining us as the co-host.

00:01:51.639 --> 00:01:58.199
Art is a private investor and former chairman, CEO, and president of Oppenheimer Funds.

00:01:58.919 --> 00:02:03.480
And Art, I'd love to kick things off with having you introduce yourself, maybe sharing

00:02:03.480 --> 00:02:08.520
a bit about your journey and also something you like to do outside of work too.

00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:09.479
Sure, sure.

00:02:09.479 --> 00:02:12.199
Well, thanks very much for inviting me.

00:02:13.080 --> 00:02:21.000
I'm speaking to you all from New York City where we have yet to see winter start.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:25.720
Supposedly we might get some snow this weekend but we haven't had any snow at all this winter

00:02:25.720 --> 00:02:26.759
so that's strange.

00:02:26.759 --> 00:02:34.119
I'm sitting here in my study and I'm drinking out of my Gigi plot mug which was designed

00:02:34.119 --> 00:02:35.639
by Selena Carter.

00:02:35.639 --> 00:02:42.600
She graciously let me put this design on what is one of those sites that lets you print

00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:44.279
out your own t-shirts and stuff like that.

00:02:44.279 --> 00:02:46.440
So I had myself a coffee mug made with that.

00:02:47.960 --> 00:02:52.199
Anyway, so I'm technically retired.

00:02:52.199 --> 00:02:54.119
I used to work on Wall Street.

00:02:54.119 --> 00:03:01.160
I was a money manager for most of my time before I went into a leadership position at

00:03:01.160 --> 00:03:02.039
Oppenheimer Funds.

00:03:02.119 --> 00:03:07.559
Then I stepped down when we sold the company to Invesco back in 2019.

00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:13.960
Since then I've been involved in a lot of this and that board work, philanthropic work

00:03:13.960 --> 00:03:19.160
but what I love most is being a data science hobbyist.

00:03:21.639 --> 00:03:29.639
I started working with R, the language, back in 2006, I think it was, and it just grew

00:03:29.639 --> 00:03:30.279
from there.

00:03:30.279 --> 00:03:36.759
I've just really enjoyed being able to use it first in my professional work and then

00:03:36.759 --> 00:03:39.160
now more as a hobbyist.

00:03:41.960 --> 00:03:52.279
As part of that, I really enjoyed becoming part of the R community and really appreciating

00:03:52.279 --> 00:04:01.720
the joys of open source software and its ability to put power into people's hands,

00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:06.039
to really get good work done, to do good analysis.

00:04:07.559 --> 00:04:18.440
Like anything else, you can do lousy work and it's like, as we've seen with ChatGPT,

00:04:18.440 --> 00:04:23.640
which speaks very authoritatively and confidently but sometimes spews nonsense.

00:04:24.359 --> 00:04:29.320
It's certainly dangerous to put beautiful charts and graphs into people's hands that

00:04:29.320 --> 00:04:33.559
tell the wrong story and I think that's an important narrative around

00:04:36.920 --> 00:04:39.880
how open source propagates around in organizations.

00:04:39.880 --> 00:04:41.239
That's a cautionary lesson.

00:04:41.239 --> 00:04:43.559
But anyway, we can talk a little bit about that.

00:04:45.079 --> 00:04:46.839
Anyway, that's what I do now.

00:04:47.399 --> 00:04:56.920
You can see my blog at artsteinmetz.com, where I share my data science experiments.

00:04:58.279 --> 00:05:01.000
I have to stress, I'm not a data science professional, right?

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:09.880
I'm an investment professional, so I am very much an amateur, with all the caveats that

00:05:09.959 --> 00:05:10.600
implies.

00:05:11.239 --> 00:05:18.519
But again, I really enjoy hanging out with smart people like you folks who are in the

00:05:18.519 --> 00:05:23.799
main actual data scientists or actual practitioners professionally.

00:05:26.119 --> 00:05:32.600
So, Rachel said, so what do you do for fun or something outside of work?

00:05:32.600 --> 00:05:37.559
Well, again, since I'm retired, I spend a lot of my time playing around with R.

00:05:38.200 --> 00:05:41.559
While I'm sitting at my desk, I like to ski.

00:05:42.119 --> 00:05:42.920
I like to hike.

00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:49.399
I was a home brewer.

00:05:49.399 --> 00:05:55.320
I kind of retired from that when I moved from New Jersey back into New York City.

00:05:55.320 --> 00:06:01.239
But I can talk at length about IPA recipes, if anybody wants to do that.

00:06:02.200 --> 00:06:08.920
So, but again, one of the things that is nice about playing around with open source

00:06:08.920 --> 00:06:11.480
software is it's not an expensive hobby.

00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:19.559
You know, guys are famous for spending enormous amounts of money to buy gear for their hobbies,

00:06:19.559 --> 00:06:22.920
whether it's fishing or cars or whatever.

00:06:24.279 --> 00:06:30.920
Fortunately, open source software is whatever I can come up with, build in my head is what

00:06:31.480 --> 00:06:32.600
I'm spending money on.

00:06:32.600 --> 00:06:36.279
So anyway, that's enough about me.

00:06:36.920 --> 00:06:37.480
I love it.

00:06:38.519 --> 00:06:40.839
I know the mountains are getting a lot of snow.

00:06:40.839 --> 00:06:43.640
Hopefully this weekend, are you going to head up skiing?

00:06:44.200 --> 00:06:48.200
Yeah, well, I was in Big Sky, Montana at the beginning of January.

00:06:48.200 --> 00:06:53.799
And, you know, at 64 years old, I probably shouldn't do the double black diamonds.

00:06:53.799 --> 00:06:56.760
But I went down one that had thin cover.

00:06:56.760 --> 00:07:00.600
And I hooked my armpit around a tree stump.

00:07:00.600 --> 00:07:02.359
And I tore my pec.

00:07:02.359 --> 00:07:04.920
So I had orthopedic surgery a couple weeks ago.

00:07:04.920 --> 00:07:10.119
So I've got to keep staying a sling for another few weeks.

00:07:10.119 --> 00:07:15.720
But hopefully I'm going to get a little late season skiing in this year when I go back

00:07:15.720 --> 00:07:16.040
out.

00:07:16.040 --> 00:07:17.160
Hopefully won't do it again.

00:07:17.720 --> 00:07:18.760
Tear myself up again.

00:07:18.760 --> 00:07:19.320
Oh, wow.

00:07:20.440 --> 00:07:22.839
Well, I hope you're feeling okay now.

00:07:23.959 --> 00:07:28.279
So I know when we were talking yesterday a little bit, Art, you were mentioning your

00:07:28.600 --> 00:07:33.559
journey into data science started when you became a little bit frustrated by the limits

00:07:33.559 --> 00:07:34.359
of Excel.

00:07:34.359 --> 00:07:40.519
And I'm just curious to hear about how that journey first started and any tips you have

00:07:40.519 --> 00:07:45.559
for people who are also trying to help others in their organization who would love to learn

00:07:45.559 --> 00:07:45.720
too.

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:46.920
Yeah.

00:07:46.920 --> 00:07:54.519
And the disclaimer here is partly to say it was a different time then.

00:07:54.519 --> 00:08:05.480
I mean, a lot of times when we talk about cultural issues, we talk about, well, it was

00:08:05.480 --> 00:08:06.839
different back then.

00:08:06.839 --> 00:08:10.839
And it was different back then for data science.

00:08:10.839 --> 00:08:18.760
Because back then, employees at my firm couldn't install any software they pleased on their

00:08:18.760 --> 00:08:19.239
computer.

00:08:19.799 --> 00:08:24.679
And that is certainly not true in any responsible organization today.

00:08:26.119 --> 00:08:27.640
But it was a different time.

00:08:27.640 --> 00:08:37.960
So even though I could have put in the budget request for MATLAB, I'm just inherently cheap.

00:08:37.960 --> 00:08:40.840
And so when I learned about R, I was really interested in that.

00:08:40.840 --> 00:08:44.599
But I had become frustrated with the limitations of Excel.

00:08:44.599 --> 00:08:51.719
Playing around with like spreadsheet geeks will do, I had these giant spreadsheets.

00:08:51.719 --> 00:08:56.200
And they had a lot of VBA macros, visual basic macros involved with them.

00:08:56.200 --> 00:08:59.080
But they were increasingly difficult to maintain.

00:09:01.159 --> 00:09:09.239
And I would go back and pull up a project I had worked on several months earlier and

00:09:09.239 --> 00:09:14.520
was not able to figure out what the heck I was doing or what I was trying to accomplish

00:09:14.520 --> 00:09:15.320
in that thing.

00:09:15.320 --> 00:09:20.520
Or if I said, well, oh, I could use my former work because now this new project I'm working

00:09:20.520 --> 00:09:21.719
on is kind of like that.

00:09:21.719 --> 00:09:24.280
So let me reuse some of my old work.

00:09:24.280 --> 00:09:30.919
Figuring out what I did back then, what former me had done, just was a huge pain in the neck.

00:09:30.919 --> 00:09:33.400
So I was frustrated by that probably.

00:09:33.400 --> 00:09:35.320
That was probably my biggest frustration.

00:09:35.960 --> 00:09:48.919
And in addition, just the power of Excel when working on large data sets with lots of computations

00:09:51.080 --> 00:09:55.880
was also not, you know, I was running up against the limitations there.

00:09:57.400 --> 00:10:00.599
So this was, but again, this was just me.

00:10:00.599 --> 00:10:04.440
There was nothing I would say I was in production for other people to use.

00:10:04.440 --> 00:10:08.760
I had dashboards with graphs and stuff, and I would share those around in meetings.

00:10:08.760 --> 00:10:10.440
But it was really just me.

00:10:10.440 --> 00:10:13.000
So it wasn't really an enterprise application.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:23.239
But anyway, so I discovered R and was hooked immediately and was able to do some really

00:10:23.239 --> 00:10:24.119
cool work.

00:10:24.119 --> 00:10:27.080
But I was an island in the organization.

00:10:27.080 --> 00:10:33.400
And I think many of us who use open source software may feel that way.

00:10:34.119 --> 00:10:41.799
And, but slowly but surely, other people started asking me, well, how did you do that?

00:10:41.799 --> 00:10:44.840
Or that doesn't look like an Excel chart or something like that.

00:10:46.760 --> 00:10:54.760
And at the same time, my organization started becoming, in general, more quantitative.

00:10:54.760 --> 00:11:01.479
You know, we were, Oppenheimer was, and now is part of Invesco, is a, you know, a money

00:11:01.479 --> 00:11:02.200
management firm.

00:11:02.760 --> 00:11:07.080
We manage portfolios of stocks and bonds and whatever else.

00:11:08.119 --> 00:11:16.119
The, but it's, we were very much old school fundamental analysis, which is great.

00:11:17.239 --> 00:11:19.799
It just isn't, doesn't come out from the quantitative side.

00:11:19.799 --> 00:11:22.520
It's a much more touchy-feely type of thing.

00:11:23.559 --> 00:11:29.559
And, you know, like the rest of the industry, we all started becoming more interested in

00:11:30.520 --> 00:11:36.760
applying, you know, computational power to huge amounts of information.

00:11:36.760 --> 00:11:41.719
Because the price of computation is going down, the accessibility of huge information

00:11:41.719 --> 00:11:42.359
was going up.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.559
So it just was part of a natural trend.

00:11:45.559 --> 00:11:53.960
And, you know, I was able to be, you know, I was more fluent than the average portfolio

00:11:53.960 --> 00:12:00.599
manager in my firm with the techniques needed to work with that data because of just my

00:12:00.599 --> 00:12:01.880
freelance work with R.

00:12:01.880 --> 00:12:03.479
So I think that helped me out.

00:12:05.239 --> 00:12:10.200
That did not play a part in my career advancement.

00:12:10.200 --> 00:12:12.280
I don't want to suggest that at all.

00:12:12.280 --> 00:12:20.599
But I also happened to advance further in my career at Oppenheimer, ultimately becoming

00:12:20.599 --> 00:12:23.640
CEO for the last five years of my stay there.

00:12:24.119 --> 00:12:32.760
But, you know, I continued to play around with R, even though I have to admit, I was

00:12:32.760 --> 00:12:38.359
playing hooky from my real job when I was doing data science work.

00:12:38.359 --> 00:12:43.479
And, you know, I would do analysis of our funds, analysis of our competitors' funds

00:12:43.479 --> 00:12:46.919
on various types of performance metrics and so forth.

00:12:46.919 --> 00:12:49.159
But, you know, as CEO, that was not my job.

00:12:49.159 --> 00:12:52.200
There were people I could ask to do that work for me.

00:12:52.200 --> 00:12:58.200
But that's how I, you know, that was sort of a release for me and a little bit of an

00:12:58.200 --> 00:12:59.960
unwind for doing that.

00:12:59.960 --> 00:13:09.400
But at the same time, people in my organization understood that, you know, I was very sympathetic

00:13:09.400 --> 00:13:13.159
or receptive to using these kinds of tools in the organization.

00:13:13.719 --> 00:13:21.559
And I was constantly evangelizing about or thinking about ways that our organization

00:13:21.559 --> 00:13:29.719
could apply more quantitative techniques to upping our game all across the business.

00:13:30.520 --> 00:13:36.200
So, you know, people, other, you know, there are other islands around our company of people

00:13:36.200 --> 00:13:41.000
who are using this kind of stuff, whether it was R or Python or other tools.

00:13:41.960 --> 00:13:47.400
And they knew that I was, you know, very much a champion of those sorts of things.

00:13:47.479 --> 00:13:52.599
What that allowed us to do is from their standpoint, practically, it allowed them to fast

00:13:52.599 --> 00:13:59.239
track permission to use these tools or to get software updates or things like that.

00:13:59.239 --> 00:14:04.440
Because as I said, you know, we all got to the point where you couldn't just install

00:14:04.440 --> 00:14:06.679
whatever the heck you wanted on your computer.

00:14:06.679 --> 00:14:11.640
So at least they knew that the IT guys were going to be sympathetic to their requests.

00:14:12.440 --> 00:14:17.719
You know, and this is a dichotomy I'm sure many of you see in your organizations all the time.

00:14:17.719 --> 00:14:24.840
There's an inherent tension between the high priests in IT and the individuals on their desks

00:14:24.840 --> 00:14:29.239
who want to be free to use these open source tools.

00:14:30.200 --> 00:14:35.799
And, you know, having leadership in the organization understand and sympathizing

00:14:35.799 --> 00:14:37.559
with that is very important.

00:14:37.559 --> 00:14:48.599
One of the great things about Posit, of course, is that, you know, Posit has evolved to really

00:14:48.599 --> 00:14:56.520
facilitate easing of that tension, if you will, by providing, you know, walled garden types of

00:14:56.520 --> 00:15:03.239
tools where there can be auditing and control of the versioning of all the various packages

00:15:03.239 --> 00:15:05.960
and languages and so forth that people have on their computers.

00:15:05.960 --> 00:15:14.840
But also letting people have access to those tools and not be constrained by a large bureaucracy

00:15:15.719 --> 00:15:17.960
for every little thing they want to use.

00:15:17.960 --> 00:15:23.880
So, you know, I think Posit's doing great work on, you know, reducing friction in the enterprise.

00:15:24.440 --> 00:15:25.559
So I like that.

00:15:27.239 --> 00:15:31.479
So again, we started using these tools more, but here's the other ironic thing.

00:15:31.479 --> 00:15:33.000
So I'm an investment person.

00:15:33.640 --> 00:15:39.880
And like I said, I would like to use quantitative tools to look at time series of interest rates

00:15:39.880 --> 00:15:49.719
and stock prices and correlations and capital asset pricing model metrics around investments

00:15:49.719 --> 00:15:50.599
and stuff like that.

00:15:51.320 --> 00:15:58.280
And while I was an evangelist for this stuff, the people that were getting more excited about this

00:15:59.080 --> 00:16:03.239
were not my fellow portfolio managers and investment analysts.

00:16:03.239 --> 00:16:08.200
It was the guys in sales, the people in sales that were getting more interested in this.

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:18.919
Because like the investment people, they were getting, you know, terabytes of data

00:16:19.960 --> 00:16:24.919
from their organizations, you know, stuff that would come through our CRM,

00:16:24.919 --> 00:16:29.719
we used Salesforce, or the advisors who would sell our funds.

00:16:29.719 --> 00:16:32.200
So, you know, we were the asset managers.

00:16:32.200 --> 00:16:37.479
And then we would have advisors or stockbrokers, financial advisors,

00:16:37.479 --> 00:16:40.119
who would sell it to retail individuals.

00:16:41.080 --> 00:16:48.520
And they, for a fee, would let us see their customer data, what people were buying,

00:16:48.520 --> 00:16:52.200
what people selling, you know, whether they were buying more growth stocks

00:16:52.200 --> 00:16:54.359
or value stocks or whatever it is.

00:16:54.359 --> 00:16:56.760
And our salespeople would find those tools very valuable.

00:16:56.760 --> 00:16:58.200
But it was a data dump.

00:16:58.200 --> 00:17:00.919
It was a deluge coming from different sources.

00:17:00.919 --> 00:17:03.799
A lot of places where it was unstructured data.

00:17:05.239 --> 00:17:08.839
And even when it was structured, the formats from Morgan Stanley

00:17:08.839 --> 00:17:13.800
were different than the formats from Merrill Lynch and this kind of stuff.

00:17:14.359 --> 00:17:19.880
But our salespeople, you know, they got it sooner than our investment people

00:17:19.880 --> 00:17:26.359
that we can use open source data science tools to make some sense of this.

00:17:27.079 --> 00:17:33.000
So we did, and even today, they're the ones that are at Invesco,

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:35.560
my former colleagues at Oppenheimer, now at Invesco,

00:17:35.560 --> 00:17:39.400
are the ones pushing the envelope on this, on the distribution organization.

00:17:41.400 --> 00:17:46.439
One of the things that is a crazy thing about the mutual fund business is,

00:17:47.079 --> 00:17:50.359
you know, people buy mutual funds and then they decide to sell them.

00:17:50.359 --> 00:17:53.800
Maybe they just sell them because they need the money for other purposes.

00:17:53.800 --> 00:17:57.479
Someone dies and the money gets distributed in the estate,

00:17:57.479 --> 00:18:01.000
or the performance stinks and people stop liking the fund.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:02.520
And so they say they want out.

00:18:02.520 --> 00:18:04.920
All of those things trigger redemptions.

00:18:05.640 --> 00:18:13.959
Now, we are, the industry overall has a background redemption rate of about 25% a year.

00:18:14.920 --> 00:18:18.359
That means just to stay even with how much money we manage,

00:18:18.359 --> 00:18:26.199
we have to go out and resell 25% of our total asset base every year.

00:18:26.199 --> 00:18:28.439
So that's billions and billions of dollars.

00:18:28.439 --> 00:18:32.680
And the other crazy thing is, well, it's not crazy at all, but we sell,

00:18:32.680 --> 00:18:35.319
we pay commissions to salespeople.

00:18:35.319 --> 00:18:39.880
So getting a dollar is much more expensive than keeping a dollar.

00:18:40.520 --> 00:18:46.199
So we could drop a lot of money right to the bottom line if we could cut our redemption rate.

00:18:46.199 --> 00:18:51.160
So I sat down with our salespeople and that became kind of a thing I was

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:54.520
really pounding the table about.

00:18:55.160 --> 00:19:00.439
So they went and we put together a data science team of about nine PhD

00:19:02.920 --> 00:19:04.199
data analytics people.

00:19:05.239 --> 00:19:08.119
And this was all coming out of the sales budget.

00:19:08.119 --> 00:19:11.800
They cheerfully paid for all this.

00:19:11.800 --> 00:19:15.400
And we started looking at how can we reduce our redemption rate?

00:19:15.400 --> 00:19:19.079
At that time, our redemption rate was running above the industry average of about 27.

00:19:19.640 --> 00:19:23.079
And the nice thing when you're a big firm, you can run A, B tests.

00:19:23.079 --> 00:19:27.800
We tried different kinds of interventions, different kind of marketing materials,

00:19:28.760 --> 00:19:35.719
changed who we visited and how much time we spent with people,

00:19:35.719 --> 00:19:37.640
tried so many different things.

00:19:37.719 --> 00:19:39.880
And we found out what worked and what didn't work.

00:19:40.439 --> 00:19:44.760
And if people want some of the details, I can go into that.

00:19:45.560 --> 00:19:49.479
But the bottom line is that we were able to cut our redemption rate

00:19:49.479 --> 00:19:52.040
in a couple of years from 27 to 23%.

00:19:53.079 --> 00:19:59.000
So again, that was tens of millions of profit dollars that dropped to the bottom line.

00:19:59.560 --> 00:20:07.800
And again, we were using R and RStudio to do these redemption control tests.

00:20:09.079 --> 00:20:11.640
So it was just tremendous.

00:20:12.599 --> 00:20:13.400
That's amazing.

00:20:14.280 --> 00:20:17.079
I remember seeing the blog post where you mentioned that.

00:20:17.079 --> 00:20:21.479
So I want to make sure to go grab that and put it into the chat for everybody too.

00:20:23.719 --> 00:20:27.239
But something else I wanted to ask you is on the Hangouts,

00:20:27.239 --> 00:20:32.199
we talk a lot about best practices for sharing our work with executives.

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:36.839
And it's rare that we actually have the executive here on the call.

00:20:36.839 --> 00:20:43.079
So as a former CEO, I was wondering if you have any tips for all of us on

00:20:43.880 --> 00:20:48.119
communicating with executives and sharing our data work with them?

00:20:48.599 --> 00:20:49.099
Yeah.

00:20:50.280 --> 00:20:57.880
The two key points.

00:20:57.880 --> 00:21:07.239
One is, you know, data visualization is the most powerful way to tell,

00:21:07.239 --> 00:21:09.400
get a narrative across quickly.

00:21:10.040 --> 00:21:14.599
So spend time learning good visualization techniques.

00:21:14.599 --> 00:21:22.119
Even if you're a math whiz and a coding whiz, understand good visualization.

00:21:22.119 --> 00:21:23.959
It's an aesthetic issue.

00:21:23.959 --> 00:21:24.680
It's an art.

00:21:24.680 --> 00:21:27.479
And, you know, there's lots of blogs.

00:21:27.479 --> 00:21:32.199
There's lots of literature that talk about good visualization and bad visualization.

00:21:33.800 --> 00:21:38.280
And, you know, don't use a linear scale when you should be using a log scale.

00:21:38.280 --> 00:21:40.839
You know, simple stuff like that.

00:21:41.479 --> 00:21:44.199
Because I've seen so many bad charts.

00:21:44.920 --> 00:21:51.800
And at worst, they, you know, you're going to lose your audience very quickly.

00:21:54.040 --> 00:21:55.640
Well, not necessarily even at worst.

00:21:55.640 --> 00:21:57.319
At best, maybe you're going to lose your audience.

00:21:57.319 --> 00:22:02.040
At worst, your audience will draw the wrong conclusions and make bad decisions.

00:22:02.040 --> 00:22:09.880
You know, Richard Feynman, the physicist, was on the Challenger disaster panel.

00:22:09.880 --> 00:22:12.599
That was a space shuttle that blew up on reentry.

00:22:13.239 --> 00:22:22.599
And, you know, his, one of the big takeaways in that inquiry was that PowerPoint was to blame.

00:22:23.239 --> 00:22:30.839
So the other point I would make is don't use, and I learned this from

00:22:33.800 --> 00:22:39.400
reading about the history of that inquest, is don't use a PowerPoint presentation when

00:22:39.400 --> 00:22:44.280
you should be using a memo that people can read and a narrative.

00:22:44.280 --> 00:22:49.000
Because all of you are familiar with the problem of seeing a PowerPoint slide.

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:54.439
So you've got it, landscape orientation, and you've got this incredible amount of text

00:22:55.319 --> 00:23:02.040
on, you know, 12-point font text filling up a slide, you know, as if it's a slide deck.

00:23:02.040 --> 00:23:08.439
And sometimes you're subjected to sitting in a conference room having that thing with

00:23:08.439 --> 00:23:13.000
two minutes worth of text on a slide that you're supposed to process.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:15.400
Of course, nobody looks at that at all.

00:23:15.400 --> 00:23:18.839
And, you know, they're listening to what, hopefully, what the speaker is saying.

00:23:20.119 --> 00:23:27.800
But it's a complete waste of everyone's time to create and display this giant PowerPoint,

00:23:28.680 --> 00:23:31.319
this massive quantity of text on a PowerPoint slide.

00:23:31.319 --> 00:23:38.599
So don't use PowerPoint when a pre-read memo would do the job.

00:23:38.599 --> 00:23:41.239
And, yes, some people aren't going to read the memo.

00:23:42.760 --> 00:23:48.680
But treat your audience with respect anyway and tell them you're going to assume

00:23:50.119 --> 00:23:51.479
people have read the materials.

00:23:52.359 --> 00:23:55.319
And then have your, if you're going to have a PowerPoint or a slide deck,

00:23:56.199 --> 00:24:01.800
you know, have, you know, three, four bullet points most on a slide,

00:24:01.800 --> 00:24:06.040
and then have compelling visualizations that tell your story.

00:24:06.040 --> 00:24:11.640
That's going to earn you far more respect than showing

00:24:12.680 --> 00:24:16.040
that you've crammed your PowerPoint with a million words.

00:24:16.839 --> 00:24:17.400
Thank you.

00:24:18.119 --> 00:24:18.839
That's really helpful.

00:24:19.479 --> 00:24:23.719
I see Art, or let's see, I think, Alan,

00:24:23.719 --> 00:24:25.959
you asked a question a little bit earlier in the chat.

00:24:25.959 --> 00:24:26.760
Do you want to jump in?

00:24:29.640 --> 00:24:30.359
Yeah, sure.

00:24:30.359 --> 00:24:31.160
Hi, everybody.

00:24:32.760 --> 00:24:37.560
I'm curious, Art, if in finance or in portfolio management,

00:24:37.560 --> 00:24:43.800
if you have to be concerned about things like validated systems,

00:24:44.040 --> 00:24:50.359
software quality, the sorts of things we talk about here a lot with regards to finance,

00:24:50.359 --> 00:24:53.400
not finance, with pharma and med device and stuff,

00:24:53.400 --> 00:24:58.119
are there places in the business where you've got lots of landscape to experiment with tools?

00:24:58.119 --> 00:25:02.760
And then other places where there are folks doing work that have to be much more diligent about,

00:25:03.959 --> 00:25:06.040
you know, being validated or being controlled?

00:25:06.839 --> 00:25:09.239
And just because I don't know anything about it, are there like,

00:25:09.239 --> 00:25:12.599
you know, enterprise applications that are made for purpose

00:25:12.599 --> 00:25:14.280
for that specific kind of stuff?

00:25:14.280 --> 00:25:19.079
Or does every shop have their own tools that, you know,

00:25:20.119 --> 00:25:22.439
somebody made and everybody just keeps using them?

00:25:23.239 --> 00:25:25.239
Yeah, good question.

00:25:25.239 --> 00:25:32.359
Like health care, finance is a highly regulated industry,

00:25:32.359 --> 00:25:35.160
you know, particularly as you're, you know, consumer facing.

00:25:35.160 --> 00:25:39.560
So what we have enormous amounts of regulations over what we can say to people

00:25:40.199 --> 00:25:45.160
and what our responsibilities and potential liabilities are,

00:25:45.160 --> 00:25:49.880
are when we misrepresent what we are saying to people.

00:25:49.880 --> 00:25:54.119
Like if you say you can't lose money, this is a guaranteed win or something like that,

00:25:54.119 --> 00:25:55.239
to state the obvious.

00:25:55.239 --> 00:26:04.359
But to your point, yes, there is a huge problem in our industry around model risk.

00:26:05.160 --> 00:26:12.599
And if we use any model, and that's very liberally defined, by the way,

00:26:13.479 --> 00:26:15.719
to help us with our investment decision making,

00:26:15.719 --> 00:26:19.319
and we come back at some point or it's disclosed somehow

00:26:19.880 --> 00:26:23.160
that that model had a coding error, a bug,

00:26:24.439 --> 00:26:28.199
and gave an incorrect answer because of a bug in the code,

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:34.280
strictly speaking, we are liable for making investors whole for any losses on that.

00:26:34.280 --> 00:26:39.800
And there have been many instances of lawsuits around exactly that.

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:43.079
So we have to be very, very careful.

00:26:44.439 --> 00:26:48.520
And, you know, as you all know, there's no such thing as bug-free software.

00:26:48.520 --> 00:26:51.959
There will be errors and problems.

00:26:52.520 --> 00:26:59.160
And it's incumbent on us to self-report whether or not that caused losses.

00:27:00.119 --> 00:27:05.239
And the SEC has leveled hundreds of millions of dollars of fines

00:27:05.239 --> 00:27:10.439
over the last decade to firms for model errors.

00:27:11.160 --> 00:27:17.319
And invariably, you know, whenever people lose a lot of money

00:27:17.959 --> 00:27:22.199
in an investment that someone else is managing, there will be lawsuits.

00:27:23.079 --> 00:27:28.280
So in 2008, there was the great financial crisis and stocks went down.

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:29.880
Everything went down.

00:27:29.880 --> 00:27:30.839
There were lots of problems.

00:27:30.839 --> 00:27:33.160
And there were lots of lawsuits.

00:27:33.160 --> 00:27:35.880
And the heart of many of those were,

00:27:36.920 --> 00:27:38.920
I lost money and I'm mad about it.

00:27:38.920 --> 00:27:41.000
I want somebody to make me whole.

00:27:41.560 --> 00:27:44.359
So now if I'm hiring a lawyer,

00:27:44.359 --> 00:27:51.079
how do I craft a case that says it was somebody else's fault

00:27:51.079 --> 00:27:56.680
other than just the market and I therefore should be made whole?

00:27:56.680 --> 00:27:58.839
One of the first things they go looking for,

00:27:58.839 --> 00:28:01.800
whether or not there were models involved in making the trades,

00:28:01.800 --> 00:28:03.959
whether any robots were doing the work,

00:28:03.959 --> 00:28:06.119
and then were there bugs in that.

00:28:06.119 --> 00:28:14.359
So there are, every model is different.

00:28:14.359 --> 00:28:16.040
Every process is different.

00:28:16.040 --> 00:28:22.439
There's no automated way of saying, is this bug free?

00:28:22.439 --> 00:28:23.400
Obviously.

00:28:23.400 --> 00:28:28.599
But we had, there are outside all the big accounting firms

00:28:28.599 --> 00:28:31.319
will audit your models if you pay them.

00:28:32.199 --> 00:28:33.640
So that's what we had to do.

00:28:33.719 --> 00:28:37.560
And between you and me,

00:28:37.560 --> 00:28:41.640
I don't think if there was some subtle coding error

00:28:41.640 --> 00:28:47.000
that switched a positive sign to a negative sign somewhere,

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:48.359
they're not going to discover that.

00:28:48.359 --> 00:28:51.880
But nonetheless, that becomes a legal defense that you say,

00:28:51.880 --> 00:28:57.239
well, I had an auditor review the code.

00:28:57.239 --> 00:29:01.400
But it is a huge issue in the industry.

00:29:01.479 --> 00:29:02.119
That's really interesting.

00:29:02.119 --> 00:29:02.619
Thanks.

00:29:04.040 --> 00:29:07.479
I want to make sure I go over to some of the anonymous questions

00:29:07.479 --> 00:29:08.199
that were asked too.

00:29:08.199 --> 00:29:10.199
And I just wanted to remind everybody

00:29:10.199 --> 00:29:11.800
because I know I say it in the beginning

00:29:11.800 --> 00:29:13.319
and a lot of people join after.

00:29:14.280 --> 00:29:15.640
If you want to ask questions,

00:29:15.640 --> 00:29:17.959
feel free to raise your hand on Zoom

00:29:17.959 --> 00:29:20.839
or you can put questions into the chat here.

00:29:20.839 --> 00:29:24.040
And then we also have the Slido where you can ask anonymously

00:29:24.040 --> 00:29:25.479
and we'll reshare that link

00:29:25.479 --> 00:29:28.520
because I know you can't see it after you've joined.

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:32.280
But one of the first anonymous questions was,

00:29:32.280 --> 00:29:35.239
how do we help leadership, say VP level,

00:29:35.239 --> 00:29:37.479
really understand what it is

00:29:37.479 --> 00:29:40.280
so that they don't just succumb to the buzzwords

00:29:40.280 --> 00:29:43.479
like AI, machine learning, big data, for example?

00:29:44.920 --> 00:29:48.040
Yeah, well, the buzzwords aren't useless.

00:29:48.040 --> 00:29:55.079
They, to the extent that a senior leader

00:29:55.079 --> 00:29:57.079
in the organization is going to say,

00:29:57.160 --> 00:29:59.400
if a senior leader in the organization

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:03.079
gets all excited about AI

00:30:04.439 --> 00:30:06.280
and is worried about being left behind,

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:09.319
then that means they're going to give you more support

00:30:09.319 --> 00:30:09.959
for your work.

00:30:09.959 --> 00:30:10.920
They're going to listen to you.

00:30:11.560 --> 00:30:13.560
And then you can, you know,

00:30:13.560 --> 00:30:16.599
since maybe I'm sitting in my nice corner office

00:30:17.719 --> 00:30:19.079
and I'm just hearing the buzzwords,

00:30:19.079 --> 00:30:21.079
I'm like the boss at Dilbert or something like that.

00:30:21.640 --> 00:30:25.160
And you can, but if I'm willing to listen,

00:30:25.239 --> 00:30:28.760
then you can give me a deeper understanding

00:30:28.760 --> 00:30:30.920
of what's involved.

00:30:30.920 --> 00:30:33.079
So I think the buzzwords are your friend.

00:30:34.119 --> 00:30:36.680
The important thing, I mean,

00:30:36.680 --> 00:30:38.599
if it creates any sort of urgency

00:30:38.599 --> 00:30:41.959
or, you know, creates more opportunity

00:30:41.959 --> 00:30:45.239
for, you know, data scientists

00:30:45.239 --> 00:30:48.119
to elevate the visibility of their work.

00:30:48.839 --> 00:30:51.079
The most important thing though

00:30:51.079 --> 00:30:53.880
is you have to be honest.

00:30:53.880 --> 00:30:57.479
So when I, as the boss,

00:30:58.920 --> 00:31:00.359
call you into my office and say,

00:31:00.359 --> 00:31:02.359
I heard about this chat GPT thing.

00:31:02.359 --> 00:31:04.680
Let's fire our entire, you know,

00:31:07.160 --> 00:31:10.520
our phone customer support people

00:31:10.520 --> 00:31:13.000
and just turn it over to chat GPT.

00:31:13.640 --> 00:31:15.079
You have to be honest about

00:31:15.880 --> 00:31:18.599
what these things can and can't do.

00:31:19.239 --> 00:31:20.359
And one of the things that,

00:31:21.800 --> 00:31:23.079
this will never change.

00:31:23.079 --> 00:31:27.479
This has been true since the times of Hammurabi

00:31:27.479 --> 00:31:31.719
that, you know, subordinates will come

00:31:31.719 --> 00:31:33.160
into the boss's office

00:31:33.160 --> 00:31:35.239
and they'll blow sunshine up your skirt.

00:31:35.880 --> 00:31:38.599
And, you know, avoiding that,

00:31:39.319 --> 00:31:40.920
getting an environment,

00:31:41.479 --> 00:31:42.920
and this is important.

00:31:42.920 --> 00:31:45.079
This is what the bosses have to do.

00:31:45.079 --> 00:31:46.680
What the leaders have to do

00:31:46.680 --> 00:31:50.359
is create an environment of trust

00:31:51.160 --> 00:31:53.959
where people can deliver bad news

00:31:53.959 --> 00:31:58.359
about what something can and cannot accomplish

00:31:59.880 --> 00:32:00.680
to the boss.

00:32:01.400 --> 00:32:04.040
And they can't be afraid of saying,

00:32:04.599 --> 00:32:06.280
you know, sorry boss,

00:32:06.280 --> 00:32:10.680
you know, chat GPT isn't the be all and end all.

00:32:13.160 --> 00:32:14.680
And, you know,

00:32:15.800 --> 00:32:18.280
I mean, again, I experienced this firsthand,

00:32:18.280 --> 00:32:19.079
but, you know, people,

00:32:19.479 --> 00:32:20.439
if I would say,

00:32:20.439 --> 00:32:22.439
oh, this sounds like fun, let's do it.

00:32:22.439 --> 00:32:24.760
Or this looks like this will be interesting, let's do it.

00:32:24.760 --> 00:32:26.439
People will start scrambling around

00:32:26.439 --> 00:32:30.439
and try and do it because the boss likes it.

00:32:32.280 --> 00:32:35.079
And well, on one sense I'll say good

00:32:35.079 --> 00:32:36.280
because I'm the boss.

00:32:36.280 --> 00:32:38.680
I'd like to have some influence over what people do.

00:32:39.319 --> 00:32:44.199
But you have to have the courage to say,

00:32:45.160 --> 00:32:46.920
no, this is not going to work

00:32:46.920 --> 00:32:48.280
if it's not going to work.

00:32:49.839 --> 00:32:51.160
Thank you.

00:32:51.719 --> 00:32:55.079
I really like that reframing of like buzzwords

00:32:55.079 --> 00:32:56.439
can be your friend as well

00:32:57.079 --> 00:32:59.400
when you're trying to get your point across

00:32:59.400 --> 00:33:00.280
or highlight your work.

00:33:00.920 --> 00:33:01.420
Yeah.

00:33:02.520 --> 00:33:05.319
Dave, I see you had asked a question a bit earlier too.

00:33:05.319 --> 00:33:06.359
Do you want to jump in next?

00:33:07.160 --> 00:33:08.199
Sure. Thanks, Rachel.

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:11.479
Hi Art, this is Dave Shea from Posit.

00:33:13.560 --> 00:33:16.760
The description you have of your experience at Oppenheimer,

00:33:16.760 --> 00:33:19.000
I know it's almost backwards

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:21.079
for a lot of financial firms

00:33:21.079 --> 00:33:23.640
and definitely for other big organizations.

00:33:24.680 --> 00:33:27.000
This is data science excellence

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:29.479
and opportunity pushed from the top down.

00:33:30.920 --> 00:33:32.280
A couple of questions around that.

00:33:32.839 --> 00:33:34.359
Have you had any success

00:33:34.359 --> 00:33:40.439
in discussing with your CEO peers this opportunity

00:33:40.439 --> 00:33:42.280
and have you won them over to that?

00:33:42.920 --> 00:33:46.280
And then on the other side for folks

00:33:46.280 --> 00:33:47.479
working up the chain,

00:33:48.439 --> 00:33:51.160
what do you think is a successful way

00:33:51.160 --> 00:33:54.760
to convey that opportunity upward?

00:33:56.199 --> 00:33:58.520
Yeah, well, I think, like I said,

00:33:59.479 --> 00:34:01.000
it was a different time then,

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:02.680
but the world has come around

00:34:02.680 --> 00:34:05.479
to understanding the power of big data.

00:34:05.479 --> 00:34:06.760
Again, it's a buzzword, right?

00:34:06.760 --> 00:34:09.639
Big data, data science.

00:34:09.639 --> 00:34:12.760
And my alma mater, Denison University,

00:34:12.760 --> 00:34:16.919
has launched a whole school around data science,

00:34:16.919 --> 00:34:19.560
data analytics, and it's a liberal arts college.

00:34:19.560 --> 00:34:21.479
I was a Russian major in college.

00:34:23.959 --> 00:34:27.000
But I think CEOs today very much,

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:28.919
even if they don't necessarily understand it,

00:34:28.919 --> 00:34:30.199
going back to the buzzwords,

00:34:30.199 --> 00:34:31.560
they think it's important

00:34:31.560 --> 00:34:35.239
and they need to pay attention to it.

00:34:36.840 --> 00:34:39.159
So I don't see much resistance to that.

00:34:39.159 --> 00:34:40.360
You know, it's funny though,

00:34:40.360 --> 00:34:44.280
like I said, the investment people in my organization

00:34:45.560 --> 00:34:48.120
to some extent still are very old school.

00:34:48.120 --> 00:34:51.639
They are very wary of quantitative techniques

00:34:51.639 --> 00:34:55.000
because there are many quant funds out there

00:34:55.000 --> 00:34:57.239
and some of them do great work.

00:34:59.479 --> 00:35:01.959
We are fundamental investors.

00:35:01.959 --> 00:35:04.199
So it's reading annual reports

00:35:04.199 --> 00:35:05.800
and talking to management,

00:35:05.800 --> 00:35:07.159
visiting the factories

00:35:07.159 --> 00:35:08.439
or whatever it happens to be.

00:35:08.439 --> 00:35:09.800
That's fundamental management.

00:35:09.800 --> 00:35:11.159
We try to beat the market

00:35:11.159 --> 00:35:13.959
doing better research in those lines.

00:35:13.959 --> 00:35:15.560
And there was a lot of resistance

00:35:15.560 --> 00:35:18.040
to quantitative techniques

00:35:18.040 --> 00:35:20.040
because we're fundamental.

00:35:20.040 --> 00:35:22.360
We're not gonna let the robots take over.

00:35:22.360 --> 00:35:24.120
Now, the argument I would make,

00:35:24.120 --> 00:35:26.360
I did make to, you know,

00:35:26.360 --> 00:35:28.679
when I became chief investment officer and then CEO,

00:35:28.679 --> 00:35:33.000
the argument I would make to the investment people,

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:35.959
and I was not going to push anything down their throats.

00:35:35.959 --> 00:35:39.239
I was trying to evangelize to make them want to do this.

00:35:40.040 --> 00:35:40.840
But I said to them,

00:35:40.840 --> 00:35:44.520
look, this isn't about the robots taking your jobs

00:35:44.520 --> 00:35:46.520
or we're gonna, you know,

00:35:46.520 --> 00:35:48.439
I mean, literally, that's what they were worried about,

00:35:49.080 --> 00:35:51.239
that we were just gonna make these quant funds

00:35:51.239 --> 00:35:52.199
because we had some.

00:35:52.199 --> 00:35:53.959
We launched because they would,

00:35:53.959 --> 00:35:55.879
nobody would come around on the fundamental side.

00:35:55.879 --> 00:35:57.399
We launched some quant funds.

00:36:02.679 --> 00:36:06.199
The argument I made with limited success was,

00:36:06.199 --> 00:36:08.199
look, I'm not talking about getting rid of you.

00:36:08.199 --> 00:36:10.199
I'm saying you have been digging ditches

00:36:10.199 --> 00:36:13.080
with a shovel your whole career.

00:36:13.080 --> 00:36:15.159
Now, I come and give you a backhoe.

00:36:15.959 --> 00:36:16.919
You're not gonna use it.

00:36:17.639 --> 00:36:19.639
You know, it's a force multiplier

00:36:19.639 --> 00:36:21.719
if you can apply these quantitative tools

00:36:21.719 --> 00:36:25.719
to suddenly process far more data

00:36:25.719 --> 00:36:27.159
than you used to be able to.

00:36:27.159 --> 00:36:29.959
It's making your analysts far more efficient.

00:36:32.679 --> 00:36:34.040
But, you know, like I said,

00:36:34.040 --> 00:36:35.959
in terms of the rest of other CEOs,

00:36:35.959 --> 00:36:37.879
other people in asset management,

00:36:38.199 --> 00:36:40.439
everyone's come around, I think, to that.

00:36:40.439 --> 00:36:42.520
And, you know, how do you get,

00:36:42.520 --> 00:36:44.919
so I mean, I would be interested in hearing

00:36:44.919 --> 00:36:46.520
what other people say about this

00:36:46.520 --> 00:36:49.719
because you folks are more mid-career,

00:36:49.719 --> 00:36:53.000
early career than I certainly am as retired.

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:54.360
You would probably have a better sense

00:36:54.360 --> 00:36:57.320
of the receptivity in your organization

00:36:57.320 --> 00:37:00.360
to using more powerful quantitative tools.

00:37:02.879 --> 00:37:06.040
I noticed a few people resonated with

00:37:06.040 --> 00:37:08.520
when you said living on your own island.

00:37:08.520 --> 00:37:11.399
So a lot of people were feeling that too.

00:37:12.679 --> 00:37:14.199
You know, what I hope,

00:37:14.199 --> 00:37:17.080
again, this worked to some extent in my organization,

00:37:18.520 --> 00:37:20.520
and it's happening right now at Invesco too,

00:37:20.520 --> 00:37:21.479
I should add.

00:37:21.479 --> 00:37:23.239
People look over your shoulder and say,

00:37:23.239 --> 00:37:24.360
wow, that is cool.

00:37:24.360 --> 00:37:25.719
How do you do that?

00:37:25.719 --> 00:37:29.959
Or I see a way I could apply what you're doing there.

00:37:29.959 --> 00:37:32.439
So for instance, at Invesco right now,

00:37:32.760 --> 00:37:35.959
and this started after I had left,

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:38.600
one of their folks, again, in sales

00:37:39.399 --> 00:37:42.919
has created a shiny app that

00:37:45.879 --> 00:37:48.040
if one of our customers,

00:37:48.040 --> 00:37:49.879
which is to say our brokers,

00:37:49.879 --> 00:37:51.399
shares their customers,

00:37:51.399 --> 00:37:53.800
which is the end investor,

00:37:53.800 --> 00:37:55.879
their portfolios with us,

00:37:55.879 --> 00:37:57.479
what other funds they're invested in,

00:37:57.479 --> 00:37:59.639
what other stocks are invested in, whatever,

00:37:59.639 --> 00:38:02.840
we can run an analysis on that

00:38:02.840 --> 00:38:07.800
to help them optimize their tax situation,

00:38:07.800 --> 00:38:09.639
when they should take capital gains,

00:38:09.639 --> 00:38:11.320
when they should take capital losses,

00:38:11.959 --> 00:38:15.159
what they should sell to realize a loss or a gain,

00:38:15.159 --> 00:38:16.840
and then if they want to keep

00:38:16.840 --> 00:38:19.239
the portfolio complexion the same,

00:38:19.239 --> 00:38:22.439
what should they then buy on the other side

00:38:23.479 --> 00:38:26.120
to keep the portfolio complexion,

00:38:26.280 --> 00:38:29.639
the overall risk or aggressiveness,

00:38:29.639 --> 00:38:30.600
whatever it happens to be,

00:38:30.600 --> 00:38:33.080
the overall portfolio complexion the same.

00:38:33.080 --> 00:38:35.560
So he built a shiny app that does that.

00:38:35.560 --> 00:38:37.159
So all of our salespeople,

00:38:37.159 --> 00:38:39.159
all of Invesco salespeople

00:38:39.159 --> 00:38:43.159
can look at all of the advisors that they serve

00:38:43.800 --> 00:38:45.800
and look at that,

00:38:45.800 --> 00:38:48.199
and that generates discussions.

00:38:48.199 --> 00:38:51.879
And salespeople love to have opportunities

00:38:51.879 --> 00:38:53.959
to call their customers up

00:38:53.959 --> 00:38:55.639
and have an interesting discussion

00:38:55.879 --> 00:38:57.800
and say, look, here's an issue you have

00:38:57.800 --> 00:38:59.639
that I think I can help you solve.

00:38:59.639 --> 00:39:01.879
That's salespeople love getting that kind of a lead.

00:39:01.879 --> 00:39:03.639
So it generates that sort of thing.

00:39:03.639 --> 00:39:06.840
And then if the discussion goes further with one click,

00:39:06.840 --> 00:39:10.600
they generate a detailed PDF report

00:39:10.600 --> 00:39:17.320
on exactly what the gains and losses are

00:39:17.320 --> 00:39:18.679
across the portfolio.

00:39:18.679 --> 00:39:21.800
And the salespeople just love that tool,

00:39:21.800 --> 00:39:23.719
but it's one individual.

00:39:24.439 --> 00:39:27.639
And my fear is that it dies with him.

00:39:27.639 --> 00:39:29.159
If he leaves the firm,

00:39:29.159 --> 00:39:30.360
who's gonna maintain that?

00:39:31.239 --> 00:39:32.360
It's an island.

00:39:32.360 --> 00:39:36.919
And yet it's a shiny app in production

00:39:36.919 --> 00:39:41.159
that has become an extremely popular tool

00:39:42.679 --> 00:39:44.439
among 200 salespeople.

00:39:45.080 --> 00:39:50.520
So it's an interesting opportunity.

00:39:51.479 --> 00:39:55.320
And this person is not naturally

00:39:55.320 --> 00:39:58.760
a real outgoing, gregarious individual.

00:39:59.879 --> 00:40:03.479
So I've been trying to encourage him

00:40:03.479 --> 00:40:07.479
to think about ways that he can let other people know

00:40:07.479 --> 00:40:08.840
this is a tool that he built

00:40:09.560 --> 00:40:12.760
and you can have this kind of a cool tool also

00:40:14.439 --> 00:40:15.239
in your area.

00:40:15.239 --> 00:40:17.239
So getting them off the island,

00:40:17.800 --> 00:40:18.760
I've made it a...

00:40:21.159 --> 00:40:22.520
I have no vested interest in this.

00:40:22.520 --> 00:40:24.120
I've made it my mission.

00:40:25.399 --> 00:40:26.040
Absolutely.

00:40:26.840 --> 00:40:29.320
It's really interesting to think about

00:40:29.320 --> 00:40:32.280
maybe some of us could be targeting our work

00:40:32.280 --> 00:40:34.679
to different groups of people within the company

00:40:34.679 --> 00:40:37.879
like sales, which we may not have thought of before.

00:40:37.879 --> 00:40:40.360
And I see somebody had asked an anonymous question

00:40:41.719 --> 00:40:43.239
that sales was so interested

00:40:43.239 --> 00:40:45.239
in the data was really interesting to them.

00:40:45.239 --> 00:40:46.360
And they asked,

00:40:46.360 --> 00:40:48.520
were there any groups that you were surprised

00:40:48.520 --> 00:40:49.719
weren't interested?

00:40:49.719 --> 00:40:51.320
And why do you think that was?

00:40:52.040 --> 00:40:53.560
Yeah, well, again, I've already told the story

00:40:53.560 --> 00:40:54.600
about the investment people.

00:40:56.120 --> 00:40:57.959
And they were pretty skeptical.

00:40:57.959 --> 00:40:59.719
The other group as well,

00:41:01.399 --> 00:41:03.719
is it worth the cost?

00:41:04.600 --> 00:41:07.159
What's the IRR on this investment?

00:41:07.159 --> 00:41:11.080
And again, in the anecdote I shared

00:41:11.080 --> 00:41:13.000
about redemption control,

00:41:13.639 --> 00:41:15.320
the IRR was strongly positive,

00:41:15.320 --> 00:41:17.639
but it's not always gonna be that way.

00:41:17.639 --> 00:41:18.760
But I think it is important

00:41:18.760 --> 00:41:21.239
to have a clear eyed understanding

00:41:21.239 --> 00:41:24.840
of what the IRR is going to be

00:41:24.840 --> 00:41:26.840
on a project like this.

00:41:27.800 --> 00:41:29.239
What I would not be concerned about

00:41:29.239 --> 00:41:30.840
is whether there are enough projects

00:41:30.840 --> 00:41:32.040
for a data science team.

00:41:32.040 --> 00:41:33.719
And most organizations,

00:41:36.360 --> 00:41:39.800
you might have a particular use case

00:41:39.800 --> 00:41:41.560
when you spin up some kind

00:41:41.560 --> 00:41:42.919
of a data science organization.

00:41:43.479 --> 00:41:45.080
But like I said, very quickly,

00:41:45.080 --> 00:41:47.800
other people will see the cool stuff

00:41:47.800 --> 00:41:50.760
that is happening and want in on it.

00:41:52.760 --> 00:41:58.679
So, oh, one of the questions I saw

00:41:58.679 --> 00:42:00.040
going back into the chat was,

00:42:00.919 --> 00:42:03.719
what books you might recommend

00:42:03.719 --> 00:42:06.360
that help you throughout your career

00:42:06.360 --> 00:42:07.320
to develop your mindset

00:42:07.320 --> 00:42:08.760
as a data science CEO?

00:42:09.320 --> 00:42:10.600
Well, let's see here.

00:42:11.879 --> 00:42:16.520
I already talked about Tufte, right?

00:42:16.520 --> 00:42:20.520
So, he's got a whole bunch of books,

00:42:20.520 --> 00:42:23.080
but this is the one that started it all.

00:42:23.719 --> 00:42:28.280
The visual, I got this,

00:42:28.280 --> 00:42:30.600
the visual state of information.

00:42:31.479 --> 00:42:34.600
And this guy is kind of a lovable curmudgeon,

00:42:34.600 --> 00:42:35.320
kind of a crank,

00:42:35.879 --> 00:42:38.840
but he's passionate about making sure

00:42:38.840 --> 00:42:40.360
that your visualizations

00:42:40.360 --> 00:42:41.639
convey the information

00:42:41.639 --> 00:42:43.639
that you want them to convey.

00:42:43.639 --> 00:42:46.360
So, his whole series of books,

00:42:46.360 --> 00:42:51.320
they're all classics in the field.

00:42:53.479 --> 00:42:55.879
Another one to pull off the show

00:42:55.879 --> 00:42:58.600
that I think is a ripping yarn

00:42:59.239 --> 00:43:01.719
is Against the Gods by Peter Bernstein,

00:43:01.719 --> 00:43:03.399
the remarkable story of risk.

00:43:03.399 --> 00:43:05.159
For anyone who wants to understand

00:43:05.800 --> 00:43:10.360
how we went from thinking

00:43:10.360 --> 00:43:12.760
everything is just in the hands of the gods

00:43:12.760 --> 00:43:13.959
and it's all fate

00:43:13.959 --> 00:43:17.719
to being able to price derivatives

00:43:18.919 --> 00:43:21.560
using normal distributions

00:43:21.560 --> 00:43:23.080
and understanding probability.

00:43:23.080 --> 00:43:23.959
This is a great book

00:43:23.959 --> 00:43:26.199
and this is not dry in the least,

00:43:26.199 --> 00:43:27.639
but I think it's very useful

00:43:27.639 --> 00:43:28.679
for understanding

00:43:28.679 --> 00:43:30.679
how the history of risk evolved.

00:43:31.560 --> 00:43:33.159
The ancient Romans

00:43:33.159 --> 00:43:35.080
were inveterate gamblers

00:43:35.159 --> 00:43:37.239
but they had no sense of probability.

00:43:37.239 --> 00:43:39.719
So, if you wanted to go play cards,

00:43:40.360 --> 00:43:41.639
play poker with the Romans,

00:43:41.639 --> 00:43:42.679
you could really fleece them.

00:43:43.879 --> 00:43:46.199
But it was Blaise Pascal

00:43:47.239 --> 00:43:51.879
who was a philosopher and mathematician

00:43:51.879 --> 00:43:54.919
who really developed probability

00:43:54.919 --> 00:43:58.040
and he did it because he was a gambler.

00:43:58.600 --> 00:44:03.560
So, you know, there's another book

00:44:03.560 --> 00:44:05.479
that got me thinking about it.

00:44:05.479 --> 00:44:06.280
It's out of reach

00:44:06.280 --> 00:44:08.840
because it's over in my business books section.

00:44:10.600 --> 00:44:12.040
But there's another book

00:44:12.040 --> 00:44:17.000
called The Outsiders by Richard?

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:18.600
His last name is Thorndike.

00:44:20.199 --> 00:44:22.120
I'm not sure his first name is Richard,

00:44:22.120 --> 00:44:24.360
but he has a great book

00:44:24.360 --> 00:44:25.399
for thinking about

00:44:25.560 --> 00:44:29.719
how CEOs should think about

00:44:29.719 --> 00:44:32.360
maximizing the value of their businesses.

00:44:33.560 --> 00:44:36.280
And that had a profound influence on me.

00:44:36.280 --> 00:44:39.159
One of the things that is true,

00:44:39.719 --> 00:44:42.040
if you look at most mergers

00:44:42.040 --> 00:44:43.399
of publicly traded companies,

00:44:43.399 --> 00:44:44.439
the vast majority,

00:44:47.239 --> 00:44:49.239
three plus three equals five,

00:44:50.199 --> 00:44:52.840
which is to say that the mergers

00:44:52.840 --> 00:44:55.239
are usually destructive of shareholder value.

00:44:56.040 --> 00:44:59.800
And I won't name names,

00:44:59.800 --> 00:45:03.560
but I've experienced this so often

00:45:03.560 --> 00:45:05.399
in my career.

00:45:05.399 --> 00:45:08.600
And the problem is the CEO

00:45:08.600 --> 00:45:10.120
of the combined entity

00:45:10.120 --> 00:45:11.399
now gets to say,

00:45:11.399 --> 00:45:13.800
I grew the company.

00:45:13.800 --> 00:45:15.000
It's much bigger now.

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:16.760
And he, of course, he or she,

00:45:18.040 --> 00:45:19.639
obviously, usually a white man,

00:45:19.959 --> 00:45:22.199
obviously, usually a white man,

00:45:23.159 --> 00:45:26.679
is running a much bigger organization.

00:45:27.239 --> 00:45:29.239
And that could be used

00:45:29.239 --> 00:45:31.159
to justify the board

00:45:31.159 --> 00:45:32.679
paying them a lot more

00:45:32.679 --> 00:45:34.439
generous compensation.

00:45:34.439 --> 00:45:36.439
And he gets the reputation

00:45:36.439 --> 00:45:37.320
as a deal maker.

00:45:39.159 --> 00:45:41.800
But the problem is if the company,

00:45:41.800 --> 00:45:44.360
if the two companies were worth six apart

00:45:44.360 --> 00:45:45.639
and they're now worth five,

00:45:46.919 --> 00:45:47.800
you lost money.

00:45:48.520 --> 00:45:49.800
You didn't do a good job.

00:45:49.800 --> 00:45:51.080
This book, The Outsiders,

00:45:51.800 --> 00:45:54.360
really cracks that open

00:45:54.360 --> 00:45:55.800
and does a lot of,

00:45:55.800 --> 00:45:57.320
as business books like to do,

00:45:57.320 --> 00:45:58.600
there's a lot of anecdotes

00:45:58.600 --> 00:45:59.399
and case studies,

00:46:00.600 --> 00:46:02.840
shows a few CEOs

00:46:02.840 --> 00:46:04.280
who understood that

00:46:04.280 --> 00:46:05.800
and bucked that trend

00:46:05.800 --> 00:46:06.919
and really thought about

00:46:06.919 --> 00:46:10.199
how to grow the wealth

00:46:10.199 --> 00:46:13.959
of their shareholders,

00:46:13.959 --> 00:46:15.320
which is what they're accountable to.

00:46:16.280 --> 00:46:21.080
One of the things that

00:46:21.080 --> 00:46:23.479
whenever companies get mashed together,

00:46:23.479 --> 00:46:25.719
there's talk of cost savings, right?

00:46:25.719 --> 00:46:26.679
You have synergies,

00:46:26.679 --> 00:46:28.679
economies of scale, et cetera.

00:46:28.679 --> 00:46:29.959
And that's all well and good,

00:46:29.959 --> 00:46:32.840
but there's hardly ever

00:46:32.840 --> 00:46:34.919
any talk about revenue synergies

00:46:35.719 --> 00:46:37.639
because there seldom are any,

00:46:37.639 --> 00:46:38.520
even though there will be

00:46:38.520 --> 00:46:42.840
some genuflecting in that direction.

00:46:42.919 --> 00:46:44.280
Anyway, that book,

00:46:44.280 --> 00:46:46.760
I thought was very formative

00:46:46.760 --> 00:46:47.639
in my thinking

00:46:47.639 --> 00:46:49.560
as someone who was running a company,

00:46:49.560 --> 00:46:51.800
someone who bought other companies

00:46:51.800 --> 00:46:54.040
and who ultimately sold my company

00:46:54.040 --> 00:46:55.399
to another company.

00:46:56.760 --> 00:46:57.320
I love this,

00:46:57.320 --> 00:46:58.919
just grabbing the books off the back.

00:46:58.919 --> 00:47:00.919
It's like book club with art here.

00:47:00.919 --> 00:47:02.360
One of the things,

00:47:02.360 --> 00:47:04.600
this is, I'm a book,

00:47:04.600 --> 00:47:06.280
I have a fetish book.

00:47:06.280 --> 00:47:08.919
I fetishize them as objects

00:47:08.919 --> 00:47:11.639
and I'm a book fetishist.

00:47:12.520 --> 00:47:15.000
And so I really like

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:16.280
sitting in my library

00:47:16.280 --> 00:47:17.879
with a Manhattan in the evening

00:47:17.879 --> 00:47:18.679
and reading a book.

00:47:20.120 --> 00:47:20.620
Nice.

00:47:21.239 --> 00:47:22.360
So I know something

00:47:23.320 --> 00:47:25.879
that you are also really involved with

00:47:26.439 --> 00:47:30.360
is enhancing data literacy

00:47:30.360 --> 00:47:32.120
and mathematical literacy.

00:47:33.159 --> 00:47:34.280
And you've been involved

00:47:34.280 --> 00:47:35.719
with Rock the Street,

00:47:35.719 --> 00:47:36.919
Wall Street's mission

00:47:36.919 --> 00:47:37.879
is to equip girls

00:47:37.879 --> 00:47:39.159
for the skills to succeed.

00:47:39.800 --> 00:47:42.280
And many other organizations.

00:47:42.280 --> 00:47:43.560
And I wanted to give some time

00:47:43.560 --> 00:47:45.320
to talk a little bit about that too

00:47:45.320 --> 00:47:46.600
and see if there's any

00:47:46.600 --> 00:47:47.399
that you'd recommend

00:47:47.399 --> 00:47:48.520
we get involved in

00:47:48.520 --> 00:47:50.840
or ways to get more involved.

00:47:51.479 --> 00:47:53.320
Yeah, thanks for asking that

00:47:53.320 --> 00:47:55.800
because it's obviously

00:47:55.800 --> 00:47:56.679
a worthwhile topic.

00:47:56.679 --> 00:47:58.280
I don't have to sell anybody here

00:47:58.280 --> 00:48:00.840
on the value of being data literate

00:48:00.840 --> 00:48:03.959
or understanding basic math.

00:48:05.639 --> 00:48:09.000
But there's a weird

00:48:10.120 --> 00:48:12.120
cultural problem I think we have

00:48:12.120 --> 00:48:13.080
certainly in this country

00:48:13.080 --> 00:48:14.919
and maybe in a lot of other countries

00:48:14.919 --> 00:48:18.199
is that it's okay to be bad at math.

00:48:18.199 --> 00:48:21.159
People are perfectly happy,

00:48:21.159 --> 00:48:22.120
maybe even proud to say,

00:48:22.120 --> 00:48:23.719
oh, I'm bad at math.

00:48:23.719 --> 00:48:24.520
Oh, you know, it's like,

00:48:25.239 --> 00:48:26.919
no one says, oh, I'm bad at reading.

00:48:28.040 --> 00:48:29.399
Oh, I'm proud to be illiterate.

00:48:31.560 --> 00:48:34.040
Numeracy should be something

00:48:34.040 --> 00:48:37.719
that we all are very proud of having.

00:48:37.719 --> 00:48:41.719
And the consequences of not being numerate

00:48:42.280 --> 00:48:43.159
are horrible.

00:48:43.159 --> 00:48:47.239
And you see, our country has become

00:48:47.239 --> 00:48:49.479
so polarized politically

00:48:49.479 --> 00:48:52.439
and the rhetoric that goes back and forth,

00:48:52.439 --> 00:48:55.479
so much of it is grounded on,

00:48:56.679 --> 00:48:58.360
so much of the persuasive power of that

00:48:58.360 --> 00:48:59.399
is grounded on people

00:48:59.399 --> 00:49:02.439
not understanding numbers, I find.

00:49:03.399 --> 00:49:05.560
And not being willing to

00:49:05.560 --> 00:49:07.560
and being very skeptical of science.

00:49:07.639 --> 00:49:09.479
Being very skeptical of experts.

00:49:10.919 --> 00:49:12.439
Like that's, those are elites

00:49:12.439 --> 00:49:13.320
or something like that.

00:49:13.320 --> 00:49:15.159
When, you know, all of you

00:49:15.800 --> 00:49:17.000
probably went to college

00:49:17.000 --> 00:49:19.239
and you learn a lot of stuff

00:49:19.239 --> 00:49:20.840
and you went on to graduate school

00:49:20.840 --> 00:49:22.040
or in your careers

00:49:22.040 --> 00:49:24.360
and you're very proud of being an expert

00:49:24.360 --> 00:49:25.000
in your field

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:26.439
and all the knowledge you've created.

00:49:26.439 --> 00:49:27.719
And the idea that that just

00:49:27.719 --> 00:49:29.639
should be devalued somehow

00:49:29.639 --> 00:49:31.080
because people need to be,

00:49:31.080 --> 00:49:32.679
feel good about being ignorant

00:49:33.320 --> 00:49:36.360
is an unfortunate state of affairs.

00:49:36.600 --> 00:49:39.320
I wish we could get back to a point

00:49:39.320 --> 00:49:41.639
where knowledge is respected

00:49:41.639 --> 00:49:43.800
in whatever field that happens to be.

00:49:43.800 --> 00:49:46.439
But certainly one of the ways to do that

00:49:46.439 --> 00:49:48.520
and make all of us more successful

00:49:48.520 --> 00:49:49.479
in our own lives

00:49:49.479 --> 00:49:55.800
is to make sure that kids understand,

00:49:58.120 --> 00:50:00.600
you know, know that it's cool

00:50:00.600 --> 00:50:01.879
is too strong a word,

00:50:01.879 --> 00:50:04.600
but cool to know math

00:50:04.600 --> 00:50:06.679
and be proud of having math skills.

00:50:07.560 --> 00:50:09.719
And so, you know, I'm,

00:50:09.719 --> 00:50:11.080
I was involved with the

00:50:11.800 --> 00:50:13.800
National Museum of Mathematics,

00:50:13.800 --> 00:50:16.520
which their mission is to make math cool.

00:50:16.520 --> 00:50:18.199
And it's not a kid's museum, by the way.

00:50:18.199 --> 00:50:20.439
They have tons of kids programs

00:50:21.560 --> 00:50:22.919
and probably most of the visitors

00:50:22.919 --> 00:50:23.959
to the museum are children.

00:50:23.959 --> 00:50:26.120
But, you know, it really shares

00:50:26.120 --> 00:50:29.000
the wonder of mathematical concepts

00:50:30.760 --> 00:50:32.600
at an adult level as well.

00:50:32.600 --> 00:50:34.280
So it's, if you're ever in Manhattan,

00:50:34.520 --> 00:50:36.120
it's absolutely worth a visit

00:50:36.120 --> 00:50:37.800
because it's a very cool

00:50:37.800 --> 00:50:40.280
exploratorium kind of museum.

00:50:40.280 --> 00:50:41.479
It's just not, you know,

00:50:42.280 --> 00:50:45.159
definite integrals printed on a poster

00:50:45.159 --> 00:50:46.280
on the wall or something.

00:50:47.080 --> 00:50:48.760
It's a very cool museum.

00:50:48.760 --> 00:50:50.120
And, you know,

00:50:51.320 --> 00:50:52.919
one of the problems is in,

00:50:52.919 --> 00:50:58.360
obviously in poor communities,

00:50:58.360 --> 00:50:59.479
underprivileged communities,

00:50:59.479 --> 00:51:00.760
whatever word you would like

00:51:00.760 --> 00:51:01.639
to describe them,

00:51:01.800 --> 00:51:03.320
minority communities,

00:51:03.879 --> 00:51:04.600
they're, you know,

00:51:04.600 --> 00:51:06.360
the schools are generally poor

00:51:06.919 --> 00:51:08.360
and Rock the Street,

00:51:08.360 --> 00:51:09.639
Wall Street brings

00:51:11.399 --> 00:51:13.639
a finance curriculum

00:51:14.199 --> 00:51:17.399
into underserved schools

00:51:17.399 --> 00:51:21.879
and using volunteers.

00:51:21.879 --> 00:51:23.959
So the business model,

00:51:23.959 --> 00:51:25.080
if you will, of Rock the Street

00:51:25.080 --> 00:51:27.080
is we get a corporate sponsor

00:51:27.800 --> 00:51:30.199
and a corporate volunteer

00:51:30.280 --> 00:51:31.959
from that sponsor

00:51:31.959 --> 00:51:33.320
and they teach a,

00:51:35.159 --> 00:51:37.879
call it a finance course to kids.

00:51:37.879 --> 00:51:38.919
And one of the things,

00:51:38.919 --> 00:51:42.280
purposes of that is to get more girls

00:51:42.280 --> 00:51:45.080
because it is focused on girls.

00:51:45.080 --> 00:51:46.120
And I use the word girls

00:51:46.120 --> 00:51:47.239
because this is high school.

00:51:48.360 --> 00:51:50.600
Get girls interested in careers

00:51:50.600 --> 00:51:51.959
and financial services.

00:51:52.520 --> 00:51:54.280
And while we know

00:51:54.840 --> 00:51:56.120
less than half of the girls

00:51:56.120 --> 00:51:57.560
are actually going

00:51:57.560 --> 00:51:58.679
to financial services,

00:51:59.560 --> 00:52:01.080
but every single one of them

00:52:01.080 --> 00:52:02.760
is going to get out of this program

00:52:02.760 --> 00:52:04.280
with basic financial literacy.

00:52:04.280 --> 00:52:05.639
They are going to understand

00:52:06.199 --> 00:52:08.199
that the credit limit

00:52:08.199 --> 00:52:11.080
on your MasterCard isn't an asset.

00:52:11.719 --> 00:52:13.479
And, you know,

00:52:13.479 --> 00:52:15.560
paying 25% a year

00:52:15.560 --> 00:52:16.840
in compound interest

00:52:16.840 --> 00:52:18.280
on your credit card balance

00:52:18.280 --> 00:52:21.080
is a really bad problem to get into.

00:52:21.639 --> 00:52:22.520
So, you know,

00:52:22.520 --> 00:52:24.760
those kinds of basic issues

00:52:24.840 --> 00:52:27.560
around life,

00:52:27.560 --> 00:52:29.000
financial life skills

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:30.679
is an important part of what they do.

00:52:30.679 --> 00:52:31.159
And of course,

00:52:31.159 --> 00:52:32.679
they go into these

00:52:32.679 --> 00:52:33.800
lesser communities.

00:52:33.800 --> 00:52:35.000
And one of the things that just like,

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:36.199
it breaks my heart

00:52:36.199 --> 00:52:38.360
and why I'm passionate about this

00:52:38.360 --> 00:52:39.320
is, you know,

00:52:40.199 --> 00:52:42.360
you know, you've all heard this term,

00:52:42.360 --> 00:52:43.560
the cycle of poverty.

00:52:43.560 --> 00:52:45.159
And there's this cycle of ignorance

00:52:45.159 --> 00:52:47.239
exists in these communities as well.

00:52:47.239 --> 00:52:48.280
And in many cases,

00:52:49.879 --> 00:52:51.959
you know, obviously the family situation

00:52:51.959 --> 00:52:53.080
is not a traditional

00:52:54.040 --> 00:52:55.639
two-parent family.

00:52:55.639 --> 00:52:56.840
And even when it is,

00:52:56.840 --> 00:52:58.520
you have issues where

00:52:58.520 --> 00:53:00.760
there isn't respect for learning

00:53:00.760 --> 00:53:02.040
in some of these families.

00:53:02.040 --> 00:53:03.800
They say, why do you want,

00:53:03.800 --> 00:53:04.760
that's not for you.

00:53:05.320 --> 00:53:06.520
You don't have a chance.

00:53:06.520 --> 00:53:08.360
You know, the system is rigged against you.

00:53:10.679 --> 00:53:11.879
Why bother?

00:53:11.879 --> 00:53:13.719
And, you know,

00:53:13.719 --> 00:53:15.959
fighting against a familial culture

00:53:15.959 --> 00:53:17.080
in some cases

00:53:17.080 --> 00:53:19.399
to give these girls the belief

00:53:19.399 --> 00:53:22.280
that yes, you can achieve.

00:53:23.000 --> 00:53:24.919
That doesn't mean the road is easy,

00:53:24.919 --> 00:53:26.840
but this is possible.

00:53:26.840 --> 00:53:27.639
And it just takes

00:53:28.439 --> 00:53:29.800
hard work and learning

00:53:29.800 --> 00:53:31.560
and you can achieve that.

00:53:31.560 --> 00:53:33.479
And so Rock the Street

00:53:33.479 --> 00:53:35.399
does great work,

00:53:35.399 --> 00:53:36.919
you know, swimming against

00:53:36.919 --> 00:53:38.840
that tide of ignorance.

00:53:38.840 --> 00:53:39.719
So it's been

00:53:41.560 --> 00:53:42.919
heartbreaking

00:53:42.919 --> 00:53:44.040
to see some of this stuff,

00:53:44.040 --> 00:53:45.399
but also so inspiring

00:53:45.399 --> 00:53:47.320
to see what the change

00:53:47.320 --> 00:53:49.479
that it can make in some kids' lives.

00:53:49.479 --> 00:53:51.399
So, you know, helping other,

00:53:51.399 --> 00:53:53.000
you know, whatever it happens to be

00:53:53.000 --> 00:53:55.800
in helping kids

00:53:58.120 --> 00:53:59.479
understand early on

00:54:00.120 --> 00:54:02.120
that they can achieve,

00:54:02.120 --> 00:54:03.879
that learning and knowledge

00:54:03.879 --> 00:54:06.199
are valuable things to have.

00:54:06.199 --> 00:54:08.520
It seems crazy to have to say that.

00:54:09.080 --> 00:54:10.679
But, you know, girls in particular

00:54:11.320 --> 00:54:12.679
are underrepresented

00:54:12.679 --> 00:54:13.639
or women in particular

00:54:13.639 --> 00:54:14.760
are very underrepresented

00:54:14.760 --> 00:54:15.879
in asset management.

00:54:15.879 --> 00:54:16.919
So that was one of the things

00:54:16.919 --> 00:54:17.800
that got me interested

00:54:17.800 --> 00:54:19.639
in Rock the Street to begin with.

00:54:21.800 --> 00:54:24.199
We need lots more representation

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:26.760
among people of color as well,

00:54:26.760 --> 00:54:29.239
but women also are, again,

00:54:29.239 --> 00:54:30.520
very underrepresented.

00:54:30.520 --> 00:54:31.879
So that's just trying to get

00:54:31.879 --> 00:54:34.280
a little more inclusivity in finance.

00:54:34.840 --> 00:54:36.439
But also what Rock the Street

00:54:36.439 --> 00:54:38.199
in particular recognize

00:54:38.199 --> 00:54:40.120
is that girls self-select

00:54:40.120 --> 00:54:41.959
out of STEM fields very early.

00:54:43.560 --> 00:54:46.360
The cultural background is such

00:54:46.919 --> 00:54:48.600
that women are told

00:54:48.600 --> 00:54:50.600
explicitly or implicitly,

00:54:50.600 --> 00:54:52.439
girls are told explicitly or implicitly

00:54:53.000 --> 00:54:54.600
that they're not good at math.

00:54:54.600 --> 00:54:55.719
They're not good at science.

00:54:55.719 --> 00:54:56.840
So that's not for them.

00:54:57.719 --> 00:55:00.520
And again, it doesn't have to be explicit,

00:55:00.520 --> 00:55:02.280
but we find that they self-select

00:55:02.280 --> 00:55:04.679
out of STEM very early in high school.

00:55:05.399 --> 00:55:06.840
And that's why it's important to,

00:55:06.840 --> 00:55:08.520
you know, there's lots of groups

00:55:08.520 --> 00:55:10.600
that help give women

00:55:10.600 --> 00:55:13.479
early career support or in college.

00:55:13.479 --> 00:55:16.280
There's Girls Who Code, for instance.

00:55:16.280 --> 00:55:17.719
That's more college level.

00:55:17.719 --> 00:55:19.239
Getting down into the high school level

00:55:19.479 --> 00:55:21.000
is critical because of this problem.

00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:22.520
Absolutely.

00:55:22.520 --> 00:55:24.040
Thank you so much for sharing that.

00:55:24.040 --> 00:55:25.479
And I did put into the chat,

00:55:25.479 --> 00:55:26.439
if there are other groups

00:55:26.439 --> 00:55:28.199
that people are involved with as well

00:55:28.199 --> 00:55:30.280
and want to share in the chat, please do.

00:55:31.239 --> 00:55:33.879
I know that our time goes by so quickly here.

00:55:33.879 --> 00:55:35.479
Is it okay if I like rapid fire

00:55:35.479 --> 00:55:37.639
a few questions at you, Art?

00:55:37.639 --> 00:55:39.560
Thank you for listening to me blab, folks.

00:55:40.360 --> 00:55:40.919
We love it.

00:55:42.120 --> 00:55:43.479
So one anonymous question,

00:55:43.479 --> 00:55:44.760
it maybe touches on things

00:55:44.760 --> 00:55:45.479
we've talked about,

00:55:45.479 --> 00:55:46.919
but can you say like,

00:55:46.919 --> 00:55:48.360
what's the number one reason

00:55:48.360 --> 00:55:51.239
you think, whether it's financial services

00:55:51.239 --> 00:55:52.040
or any company,

00:55:52.760 --> 00:55:54.679
should move to open source languages

00:55:54.679 --> 00:55:55.800
like R and Python?

00:55:57.879 --> 00:56:00.520
Yeah, because of the ecosystem,

00:56:01.800 --> 00:56:03.320
you know, with R or Python,

00:56:03.320 --> 00:56:05.080
it's the packages that will do

00:56:05.080 --> 00:56:06.280
anything you want.

00:56:06.280 --> 00:56:08.040
And these packages, of course,

00:56:08.040 --> 00:56:09.879
are constantly peer reviewed.

00:56:09.879 --> 00:56:16.600
There was a notion 10, 15 years ago

00:56:17.320 --> 00:56:19.320
that commercial software was better

00:56:19.320 --> 00:56:20.360
because you had people

00:56:20.360 --> 00:56:22.840
who were paid to mind it,

00:56:22.840 --> 00:56:24.199
whereas open source,

00:56:24.199 --> 00:56:25.239
anybody could do anything

00:56:25.239 --> 00:56:25.879
and they could,

00:56:25.879 --> 00:56:27.479
who knows whether the code is any good,

00:56:28.199 --> 00:56:30.840
which the truth was the opposite of that, right?

00:56:30.840 --> 00:56:33.239
When you've got a million eyes on something,

00:56:33.239 --> 00:56:33.959
errors are much,

00:56:34.840 --> 00:56:36.120
are spotted much more quickly.

00:56:36.120 --> 00:56:38.280
Now there were commercial software firms

00:56:38.280 --> 00:56:39.479
that had a vested interest

00:56:39.479 --> 00:56:41.479
in perpetuating that notion.

00:56:42.280 --> 00:56:45.320
There was a blog post,

00:56:45.320 --> 00:56:46.679
it was taken down at,

00:56:46.679 --> 00:56:47.719
I guess it was SaaS,

00:56:49.320 --> 00:56:52.600
where they were ripping open source code

00:56:52.600 --> 00:56:54.919
and they made a very

00:56:57.159 --> 00:56:59.320
kind of disgusting dig

00:57:01.800 --> 00:57:02.760
at Hadley Wickham.

00:57:03.399 --> 00:57:04.760
They said, you know,

00:57:04.760 --> 00:57:07.000
do you want trained professionals

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:08.040
auditing your code

00:57:08.040 --> 00:57:10.600
or do you want some drunk guy in New Zealand?

00:57:13.080 --> 00:57:15.080
Which I thought could only mean Hadley.

00:57:16.040 --> 00:57:17.560
That Hadley's from New Zealand,

00:57:17.560 --> 00:57:19.800
I have no idea whether he enjoys liquor at all,

00:57:19.800 --> 00:57:21.159
but why would they say that?

00:57:21.159 --> 00:57:21.879
It's ridiculous.

00:57:23.479 --> 00:57:24.040
But, you know,

00:57:24.040 --> 00:57:26.040
it just shows the nastiness

00:57:26.040 --> 00:57:27.080
that was out there.

00:57:27.080 --> 00:57:27.800
But it's clear that

00:57:30.280 --> 00:57:34.199
the huge ecosystem of packages

00:57:34.199 --> 00:57:36.600
maintained by passionate individuals

00:57:37.159 --> 00:57:38.760
acting as a community

00:57:38.760 --> 00:57:40.360
is what gives open sources power.

00:57:42.840 --> 00:57:44.280
I never saw that blog post,

00:57:44.280 --> 00:57:46.439
but now I'm interested to go and try and find it.

00:57:49.879 --> 00:57:52.360
One other anonymous question was,

00:57:52.360 --> 00:57:53.479
as a data person,

00:57:53.479 --> 00:57:55.159
what are the best ways to develop

00:57:56.040 --> 00:57:58.040
domain and business knowledge?

00:57:58.040 --> 00:57:59.639
They said, it benefits me to talk

00:57:59.639 --> 00:58:01.239
with the business people,

00:58:01.239 --> 00:58:02.679
but not systematically.

00:58:04.520 --> 00:58:06.199
Yeah, that's a,

00:58:07.800 --> 00:58:09.479
you know, kind of a tough problem

00:58:09.479 --> 00:58:11.320
because it requires you being

00:58:12.040 --> 00:58:14.840
an advocate for yourself in the organization,

00:58:14.840 --> 00:58:16.760
and not all of us are equipped to do that.

00:58:16.760 --> 00:58:17.320
I wasn't.

00:58:18.280 --> 00:58:21.080
My path to the top of the organization

00:58:21.080 --> 00:58:22.760
was very serendipitous,

00:58:22.760 --> 00:58:25.479
and I'll spare you the details on that as well.

00:58:25.479 --> 00:58:26.439
But, you know,

00:58:26.439 --> 00:58:28.280
you need to be able to get out there

00:58:28.280 --> 00:58:30.040
and advocate for yourself.

00:58:30.040 --> 00:58:32.280
So you have to show up

00:58:32.280 --> 00:58:33.800
and stick your nose in

00:58:35.479 --> 00:58:39.479
when there are discussions about the business.

00:58:41.399 --> 00:58:42.040
And, you know,

00:58:42.040 --> 00:58:47.159
hopefully you can present yourself

00:58:47.159 --> 00:58:49.800
as someone who is,

00:58:49.800 --> 00:58:52.600
you know, eager to help solve problems.

00:58:53.320 --> 00:58:54.360
If, you know,

00:58:54.360 --> 00:58:55.000
if you say,

00:58:55.560 --> 00:58:56.360
look, I'm here

00:58:56.360 --> 00:58:58.040
because I want to understand the problem

00:58:58.040 --> 00:59:00.199
so I can do better helping you,

00:59:00.199 --> 00:59:02.040
you know, however you want to say that.

00:59:02.040 --> 00:59:03.560
I mean, that's the kind of approach

00:59:03.560 --> 00:59:04.679
that always worked with me

00:59:05.399 --> 00:59:07.239
when people say, you know,

00:59:07.239 --> 00:59:10.280
because I certainly could have no objection

00:59:10.280 --> 00:59:12.840
to someone who's, say, in IT

00:59:13.399 --> 00:59:14.199
coming around saying,

00:59:14.199 --> 00:59:18.120
I want to understand how you run money better

00:59:18.120 --> 00:59:20.199
so I can understand your needs better.

00:59:20.760 --> 00:59:23.239
No one's going to say,

00:59:23.239 --> 00:59:24.840
oh, get out of my face.

00:59:26.520 --> 00:59:28.439
But it does require you getting out

00:59:28.439 --> 00:59:31.399
of your comfort zone, perhaps,

00:59:31.399 --> 00:59:33.080
and being an advocate for yourself.

00:59:34.600 --> 00:59:35.159
Definitely.

00:59:35.879 --> 00:59:37.080
I just want to make sure

00:59:37.080 --> 00:59:39.239
I had seen everybody's questions.

00:59:39.239 --> 00:59:40.919
So feel free to raise your hand here

00:59:41.800 --> 00:59:43.000
and, Art, if you have to run

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:43.879
at the top of the hour,

00:59:45.080 --> 00:59:45.719
just let us know.

00:59:45.719 --> 00:59:47.399
I just want to give people a last second.

00:59:47.399 --> 00:59:49.879
I'm going to go nuke my ramen

00:59:49.879 --> 00:59:51.399
when you're done.

00:59:53.719 --> 00:59:55.000
Okay, so one question

00:59:55.000 --> 00:59:58.360
I did want to ask you before you go is,

00:59:59.000 --> 01:00:00.840
what is the best career advice

01:00:00.840 --> 01:00:02.120
that you've ever received?

01:00:04.760 --> 01:00:06.840
You see, I'm not sure I could say

01:00:06.840 --> 01:00:07.879
what the best advice is.

01:00:07.879 --> 01:00:09.159
It doesn't have to be best.

01:00:09.159 --> 01:00:11.080
Maybe just something that comes to mind.

01:00:11.080 --> 01:00:13.399
I don't like using the word best, actually,

01:00:13.399 --> 01:00:14.679
when I think about it.

01:00:17.560 --> 01:00:20.919
You know, it was, you know,

01:00:20.919 --> 01:00:23.719
just, you know, don't look

01:00:25.959 --> 01:00:29.320
to your career advancement.

01:00:29.320 --> 01:00:31.560
Yes, you might be an ambitious person,

01:00:31.560 --> 01:00:33.320
but don't think about everything

01:00:33.320 --> 01:00:34.120
in terms of,

01:00:34.120 --> 01:00:36.520
how is this going to advance my career?

01:00:36.520 --> 01:00:39.959
Think in terms of how this will help others

01:00:39.959 --> 01:00:41.320
in their career.

01:00:41.320 --> 01:00:43.879
It's kind of enlightened altruism,

01:00:43.879 --> 01:00:44.600
if you will,

01:00:44.600 --> 01:00:47.000
because if you gain a reputation

